<i> SINGERS: ♪ I don't stop,</i>
<i> I don't sleep ♪</i>

02:03.657 --> 02:05.824
<i> ♪ I don't stop,</i>
<i> I don't stop, I don't stop ♪</i>

02:05.860 --> 02:07.259
<i> ♪ 'Cause I only need</i>
<i> my crew plus me ♪</i>

02:07.294 --> 02:09.595
<i> -♪ All night ♪</i>
-Oh.

02:09.630 --> 02:12.030
PATRON: Yah--
ARMAN: Call 911.

02:12.066 --> 02:13.866
Have 'em pull up
an ambulance at the lobby.

02:13.901 --> 02:15.834
The cops see any of this,
we're all busted.

02:15.870 --> 02:19.004
(laughing)

02:19.039 --> 02:21.874
-(groans)
<i> -(pop music continues)</i>

02:21.909 --> 02:25.077
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:25.112 --> 02:28.247
<i> ♪ 'Cause I only need</i>
<i> my crew plus me, all night ♪</i>

02:28.282 --> 02:31.250
<i> (dramatic music)</i>

02:31.285 --> 02:36.321
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

02:37.558 --> 02:39.224
THONY: (whispers) Kay.

02:39.260 --> 02:41.393
(quietly)
So like a spaceship,

02:41.428 --> 02:44.396
the stem cells
go back into your body

02:44.431 --> 02:46.532
carrying healthy genes,

02:46.567 --> 02:50.035
and once they land,
they take over.

02:50.070 --> 02:53.438
And then I'll be
like other kids.

02:53.474 --> 02:55.174
Yes.

02:55.209 --> 02:56.441
Are you ready?

02:56.477 --> 02:57.843
-Yes.
-Yeah?

02:57.878 --> 03:00.445
Today's the trial.
Yeah?

03:00.481 --> 03:02.281
-Yeah.
-Time for blast off.

03:02.316 --> 03:04.049
Let's go.

03:04.084 --> 03:05.384
Three...

03:05.419 --> 03:07.186
TOGETHER: Two, one.

03:07.221 --> 03:09.354
Blast off!

03:09.390 --> 03:10.923
That's good, my love.

03:12.793 --> 03:15.594
THONY: Who's this?

03:17.765 --> 03:20.365
It's the guy who saved my life.

03:22.403 --> 03:23.902
Hmm.

03:25.973 --> 03:26.939
(elevator bell dings)

03:29.610 --> 03:32.578
<i> (soft dramatic music)</i>

03:32.613 --> 03:34.580
It's not what you think.

03:34.615 --> 03:36.615
We had a bachelor party
here last night.

03:36.650 --> 03:38.250
It got a little outta hand.

03:38.285 --> 03:40.118
Hayak's daughter
is getting married.

03:40.154 --> 03:41.853
I have a cleaning crew
on the way.

03:41.889 --> 03:44.289
I just figured we could use
your special touch.

03:44.325 --> 03:46.124
Arman, wait. Um...

03:47.494 --> 03:49.461
I got something for you.

03:52.933 --> 03:54.900
Luca drew this.

03:57.638 --> 04:01.006
He wanted to thank you
for saving his life.

04:01.041 --> 04:02.708
You're his hero.

04:04.845 --> 04:06.845
His trial starts today.

04:08.482 --> 04:11.583
It wouldn't have happened
without you.

04:14.955 --> 04:17.990
Well, I'm glad Luca's
gonna be all right.

04:18.025 --> 04:19.458
I wanna pay you back
for his care

04:19.493 --> 04:22.628
-at Doctor Saroyan's clinic.
-That's not necessary.

04:22.663 --> 04:26.131
Yes, it is.
I'll need extra work.

04:26.166 --> 04:27.966
Well...(sighs)

04:28.002 --> 04:30.335
it's gonna be a busy week
with the wedding.

04:31.438 --> 04:33.372
I could use your help
here at the club.

04:33.407 --> 04:35.207
Thank you.

04:36.410 --> 04:37.676
(softly) All right.

04:44.818 --> 04:47.619
Chris, why are you
wearing flip-flops?

04:49.423 --> 04:50.322
I-I told you to wear
something nice today.

04:50.357 --> 04:52.224
Yeah, my nice shoes
are too small, remember?

04:52.259 --> 04:54.493
These are the only ones
that fit.

04:57.631 --> 04:58.930
-(door opens)
-WYATT: Hi, there.

04:58.966 --> 05:00.432
You must be Fiona.

05:00.467 --> 05:01.867
-I'm Wyatt.
-Hello.

05:01.902 --> 05:04.269
This is my son Chris,
and this is my daughter Jaz.

05:04.305 --> 05:07.039
Uh, so, Chris, I understand
that you are interested

05:07.074 --> 05:08.707
in applying for DACA,

05:08.742 --> 05:11.977
and it says here that, uh,
your dad was a U.S. citizen?

05:12.012 --> 05:13.812
-Is that right?
-Yes.

05:13.847 --> 05:15.747
Uh, we met in the Philippines,

05:15.783 --> 05:18.083
but when I found out
I was pregnant,

05:18.118 --> 05:20.552
Jacob had already
moved to the States.

05:20.587 --> 05:23.255
So-so we-we applied
for a fiancée visa,

05:23.290 --> 05:27.192
but by the time I got it,
Chris was already born.

05:27.227 --> 05:29.761
So Chris was born in Manila,
not in the U.S.

05:29.797 --> 05:31.963
Which she lied to me about
for 15 years.

05:31.999 --> 05:33.465
Chris.

05:33.500 --> 05:35.200
WYATT: And when you finally
got to America,

05:35.235 --> 05:36.735
why didn't you get married?

05:36.770 --> 05:39.504
Jacob got in a car accident,
and...

05:39.540 --> 05:41.239
and, uh, he died.

05:41.275 --> 05:42.741
- (scoffs)

05:43.711 --> 05:45.544
Well, Chris, based on this,

05:45.579 --> 05:49.047
I do think you have
a viable path to citizenship.

05:50.484 --> 05:52.851
Oh, my God, he does?
Really?

05:52.886 --> 05:54.619
It'll take some time
and resources,

05:54.655 --> 05:56.121
but I'm very confident.

05:57.491 --> 05:59.224
Why don't you look over
this fee schedule,

05:59.259 --> 06:00.659
-and then we'll talk.
-FIONA: Sure.

06:15.476 --> 06:17.442
DAYCARE WORKER: All right,
here we go, kids.

06:17.478 --> 06:19.778
-Daddy!
-Oh, hey, buddy.

06:19.813 --> 06:21.480
(chuckles)
Mwah.

06:21.515 --> 06:23.448
Are you coming
to my birthday party?

06:24.618 --> 06:25.717
You know what, Sammy?

06:25.753 --> 06:27.853
I'm gonna talk to Mommy
about that, okay?

06:28.789 --> 06:30.188
DAYCARE WORKER: Come on, Sam.
-Oh!

06:30.224 --> 06:33.024
Looks like you gotta scoot.
Have fun, pal.

06:40.234 --> 06:42.467
Good morning, ASAC Russo.

06:42.503 --> 06:44.636
I just spoke to
the U.S. Attorney's Office.

06:44.671 --> 06:45.937
Okay.

06:45.973 --> 06:48.440
They have concerns about
the Barsamian investigation.

06:48.475 --> 06:50.242
What's their problem?

06:50.277 --> 06:51.810
-You
-(chuckles)

06:51.845 --> 06:53.779
They don't think you can
deliver a prosecutable case--

06:53.814 --> 06:56.081
Well, there's nothin'
to worry about.

06:56.116 --> 06:57.649
I'm working on
a new informant.

06:57.684 --> 07:01.052
About that...
I went through your case notes.

07:01.088 --> 07:03.388
Theo LaMont made repeated
requests to get out.

07:03.424 --> 07:05.290
Oh, come on, have you
ever known an informant

07:05.325 --> 07:07.025
who didn't try
to wiggle off the hook?

07:07.060 --> 07:09.694
And now he's dead.

07:09.730 --> 07:11.563
Which is why I'm not
gonna let Arman Morales

07:11.598 --> 07:13.632
just waltz away
after killing him.

07:13.667 --> 07:15.667
It's not just Theo.

07:15.702 --> 07:17.869
It's what you did
on the Cortez case too.

07:17.905 --> 07:19.004
I know, I know.

07:19.039 --> 07:20.539
I should've taken myself
off that case.

07:20.574 --> 07:24.476
No, I should've fired you after
you slept with an informant.

07:24.511 --> 07:26.211
Pushing paper for a year
was worse.

07:26.246 --> 07:27.779
Really, Garrett?

07:27.815 --> 07:30.382
Colleen left, okay?

07:31.552 --> 07:34.352
And the reunion tour's
not lookin' so good.

07:34.388 --> 07:36.254
Do you think
I like this position

07:36.290 --> 07:38.323
that you keep putting me in?

07:38.358 --> 07:40.225
You know,
you're a good boss,

07:40.260 --> 07:41.993
but you were a lot more
fun in the field.

07:42.029 --> 07:43.695
I don't know
why you gave that up.

07:43.730 --> 07:45.964
It's called a promotion,
Garrett.

07:45.999 --> 07:47.232
(chuckles)

07:47.267 --> 07:49.034
We need fresh eyes
on the Barsamian case.

07:49.069 --> 07:50.735
That's the wrong move.

07:50.771 --> 07:52.737
This cleaning lady
is gonna come through.

07:52.773 --> 07:54.840
-I know it.
-She agreed to cooperate?

07:54.875 --> 07:57.642
Just give me some more time.

07:57.678 --> 07:59.411
I can turn her.

08:00.914 --> 08:02.347
Do I have to worry?

08:02.382 --> 08:05.016
No.
Absolutely not.

08:05.052 --> 08:07.385
If you can't turn her,
you're off the case.

08:07.421 --> 08:08.620
Mm-hmm.

08:08.655 --> 08:11.623
<i> (uneasy music)</i>

08:11.658 --> 08:13.658
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

08:13.694 --> 08:14.759
<i> (indistinct P.A. announcement)</i>

08:14.795 --> 08:16.495
Hello.

08:16.530 --> 08:18.697
This is Luca, and I'm Thony.

08:18.732 --> 08:21.266
Hi, I'm Janna,
and my son Hudson.

08:21.301 --> 08:23.068
Nice to meet you.

08:23.103 --> 08:25.070
Are you here for the trial too?

08:25.105 --> 08:26.404
-Yeah.
-Oh.

08:26.440 --> 08:28.106
I thought we were
the only ones here.

08:28.141 --> 08:31.042
We moved here from Scottsdale
to be a part of this.

08:31.078 --> 08:33.778
(exhales)
We came from the Philippines.

08:33.814 --> 08:35.447
Wow.
Okay, you win.

08:35.482 --> 08:36.448
(chuckles)

08:37.818 --> 08:40.986
Mommy, can I play
with the toys?

08:41.021 --> 08:44.389
Oh, I already sanitized
all the toys twice.

08:44.424 --> 08:46.224
BOTH: (chuckle)

08:46.260 --> 08:48.326
Yeah, go and have fun.

08:52.132 --> 08:54.099
You brought walkie-talkies?

08:55.536 --> 08:57.769
Yes,
just in case Luca and I

08:57.804 --> 08:59.804
are separated
during the procedure

08:59.840 --> 09:02.440
so we can still talk.

09:04.378 --> 09:06.511
Thony, Janna.

09:06.547 --> 09:08.346
It's so nice
to see you both again.

09:08.382 --> 09:11.116
-Thony, could I have a word?
-THONY: Mm-hmm.

09:11.151 --> 09:13.818
So Luca's preliminary
test results came back,

09:13.854 --> 09:16.521
and his liver function
is slightly abnormal.

09:16.557 --> 09:19.858
-Can I see?
-Of course.

09:19.893 --> 09:23.428
Thank you.levated.

09:23.463 --> 09:25.931
-Total bilirubin's up.
-That's right.

09:25.966 --> 09:27.933
So because of the numbers,

09:27.968 --> 09:30.302
we're going to have
to postpone the procedure

09:30.337 --> 09:32.037
and get Luca retested.

09:32.072 --> 09:34.039
Well,
he's right on the border.

09:34.074 --> 09:35.874
Yeah. Unfortunately,
it's not up to me.

09:35.909 --> 09:38.643
These clinical trials
are strictly regulated.

09:38.679 --> 09:41.713
Dr. Han in Hepatology
is waiting upstairs.

09:41.748 --> 09:44.249
There'll be a series of tests
that'll last the day.

09:46.353 --> 09:47.686
Um...

09:48.755 --> 09:50.922
Thank you, Doctor.

09:50.958 --> 09:54.192
<i> (indistinct P.A. announcement)</i>

09:59.366 --> 10:02.801
Mommy, can you open these?

10:02.836 --> 10:04.636
(sighs)

10:04.671 --> 10:07.739
Well,
actually, the doctor said

10:07.774 --> 10:10.075
that we have to wait
a little longer

10:10.110 --> 10:11.710
before you can
start the trial.

10:11.745 --> 10:13.244
Why?

10:13.280 --> 10:15.847
Because you have
to do a few more tests.

10:15.882 --> 10:18.249
-I'm sorry, peanut.
-Oh...

10:20.520 --> 10:23.521
Why don't we give these
to Hudson and his mommy?

10:23.557 --> 10:25.323
-Okay.
-THONY: Yeah?

10:26.760 --> 10:29.260
Hey, you guys hold on
to them till next time.

10:29.296 --> 10:32.364
It's just a bump
in the road, Thony.

10:32.399 --> 10:34.199
Thank you.

10:36.269 --> 10:37.402
(beep)

10:37.437 --> 10:39.971
<i> (indistinct P.A. announcement)</i>

10:43.010 --> 10:45.110
Oh, thanks.

10:46.446 --> 10:49.080
Oh, God, that's awful.
(small laugh)

10:49.116 --> 10:50.949
I don't have time for this.

10:50.984 --> 10:53.218
I need to get back to my son.

10:53.253 --> 10:55.153
What are you even doing here?

10:55.188 --> 10:57.389
I'm here because you lied.

10:58.992 --> 11:01.926
You claimed
you didn't know Arman Morales,

11:01.962 --> 11:03.728
but...

11:03.764 --> 11:05.764
here you are.

11:05.799 --> 11:08.033
That's your son, right?

11:08.068 --> 11:09.768
He's adorable.

11:11.972 --> 11:14.472
You know, lying to
a federal agent is a felony.

11:14.508 --> 11:16.374
I could deport you for that.

11:17.978 --> 11:20.211
Or...

11:20.247 --> 11:22.047
we could start over,

11:22.082 --> 11:24.249
and you can tell me
the truth this time.

11:26.687 --> 11:29.487
I clean for Mr. Morales
now and then.

11:31.124 --> 11:34.259
Which is why I want you
to be my eyes and ears

11:34.294 --> 11:36.695
inside Arman's organization.

11:36.730 --> 11:38.329
It's the perfect cover.

11:39.733 --> 11:42.867
You want me to...spy for you?

11:44.371 --> 11:46.438
-No.
-Thony, Thony, listen.

11:46.473 --> 11:50.475
If you work with me, okay,
I can offer you a way out.

11:50.510 --> 11:53.011
I can offer you protection.

11:53.046 --> 11:56.715
And if not, well,
I make one phone call,

11:56.750 --> 11:58.717
and you're on a plane
back to the Philippines.

11:58.752 --> 12:00.852
And good luck finding
a stem cell trial there.

12:00.887 --> 12:02.320
Are you threatening my son?

12:02.355 --> 12:05.123
I'm just--I'm just
stating the facts.

12:05.158 --> 12:09.260
This...this is
Luca's only chance to live.

12:09.296 --> 12:11.329
You take that away,
you kill him.

12:12.566 --> 12:15.633
<i> (somber music)</i>

12:15.669 --> 12:19.137
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

12:20.524 --> 12:21.923
Can you believe it?

12:21.958 --> 12:23.992
My baby girl
is getting married.

12:24.027 --> 12:25.527
(chuckles)

12:28.265 --> 12:31.032
You know, this wedding

12:31.067 --> 12:33.668
made me reflect on my life,

12:33.703 --> 12:36.604
all I've built,

12:36.640 --> 12:39.040
my legacy,

12:39.075 --> 12:42.076
all I have achieved
with you by my side.

12:42.112 --> 12:44.479
You are a part
of my legacy, Arman.

12:44.514 --> 12:46.080
Thank you.

12:46.116 --> 12:48.983
Hayak, it's a pleasure.
It's an--it's an honor.

12:49.019 --> 12:50.952
Now I have a favor to ask.

12:50.987 --> 12:54.889
There's an Armenian tradition
that every wedding guests

12:54.925 --> 12:57.759
bring the bride
a monetary gift.

12:57.794 --> 12:59.160
Mmm.

12:59.196 --> 13:01.496
I was wondering
if you could make sure

13:01.531 --> 13:03.598
that our valued friends

13:03.633 --> 13:06.901
understand the importance
of this tradition.

13:06.937 --> 13:08.369
Do you have
a figure in mind?

13:08.405 --> 13:10.872
Oh, I-I have this...

13:10.907 --> 13:13.641
<i> (uneasy music)</i>

13:13.677 --> 13:16.711
-(chuckles)
-What?

13:18.615 --> 13:20.215
You're serious?

13:20.250 --> 13:21.883
This is just a ballpark.

13:21.918 --> 13:24.185
I mean, use your own judgment.
I trust you.

13:26.590 --> 13:29.057
-Okay.
-Thank you.

13:29.092 --> 13:30.692
-Yeah.
- Thank you.

13:35.665 --> 13:37.065
Why didn't you ask me
to do that?

13:37.100 --> 13:39.234
That should be my job.

13:39.269 --> 13:41.436
Don't worry, son.

13:41.471 --> 13:46.174
I have a very special role
for you in mind as well.

13:46.209 --> 13:48.176
-Yeah?
-Yeah.

13:48.211 --> 13:50.144
What is it?

13:50.180 --> 13:51.679
You will see, but for now,

13:51.715 --> 13:53.848
some things are best
handled by Arman.

13:56.853 --> 13:58.520
<i> (upbeat music)</i>

13:58.555 --> 14:01.289
ARMAN: (chuckles)
Come on, Your Honor.

14:01.324 --> 14:04.158
We both know you've had
some indiscretions at the club.

14:05.695 --> 14:09.631
Just think about this 25 grand
as an investment.

14:09.666 --> 14:11.165
<i> SINGER: ♪ Let me catch</i>
<i> my breath...♪</i>

14:11.201 --> 14:12.901
ARMAN: Thank you.

14:12.936 --> 14:15.236
No, he'll be delighted
to hear that.

14:15.272 --> 14:18.172
Your Honor, thank you so much.
And we'll see you there.

14:18.208 --> 14:20.742
Well, it's a sacred
Armenian tradition, Senator.

14:20.777 --> 14:23.511
Every guest is required
to bring a monetary gift.

14:23.547 --> 14:24.946
<i> SINGER: ♪ Let me</i>
<i> catch my breath...♪</i>

14:24.981 --> 14:26.147
ARMAN: Yeah?

14:26.182 --> 14:29.284
Well, what can I say, Senator?
Thank you.

14:29.319 --> 14:32.654
Thank you, Senator.
I knew you'd come through.

14:34.224 --> 14:35.590
No, no, come on.
Too rich for your blood?

14:35.625 --> 14:37.458
Come on, Stephen, I mean,
the last time I saw you,

14:37.494 --> 14:39.761
you were cage-side
at the McGregor/Khabib fight.

14:39.796 --> 14:40.728
Yeah.

14:42.832 --> 14:45.333
What I'm asking from you
a fraction of that right now.

14:45.368 --> 14:48.036
<i> SINGER: ♪ Let me catch my... ♪</i>

14:48.071 --> 14:49.671
ARMAN: Thank you.
That's what I wanted to hear.

14:49.706 --> 14:53.174
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

14:56.746 --> 14:58.146
How's it going?

14:58.181 --> 15:00.982
Well, I made a big dent,
but look who's left.

15:04.454 --> 15:06.888
You can do it, babe.

15:06.923 --> 15:09.223
Just keep your eye
on the prize.

15:09.259 --> 15:12.393
You pull this off for Hayak,
he won't be able to say no

15:12.429 --> 15:14.495
to making you an equal
partner in the hotel.

15:17.167 --> 15:19.968
You know, he might
already be thinking that.

15:20.003 --> 15:22.036
Why do you say that?

15:22.072 --> 15:24.405
Well, I, uh, yesterday
he was, uh...

15:24.441 --> 15:25.540
he was talking about

15:25.575 --> 15:27.575
how he's been thinking
about his legacy

15:27.611 --> 15:31.012
and how I'm a big reason
his business is so successful.

15:31.047 --> 15:33.581
Because you are.

15:33.617 --> 15:35.917
But you need to think
about your legacy.

15:35.952 --> 15:38.252
-Hmm.
-What do we own?

15:38.288 --> 15:39.754
Nothing.

15:41.424 --> 15:44.559
Armando, you need to make
your ask at the reception.

15:45.829 --> 15:49.397
You know, when Hayak's
feeling like the big man.

15:49.432 --> 15:51.299
-Mm-hmm?
-(phone vibrates)

15:51.334 --> 15:56.270
(small laugh) Lucky us.
The moocher himself.

15:56.306 --> 15:58.773
-Ah...okay.
-But you have to take that.

16:00.010 --> 16:01.209
Councilman.

16:01.244 --> 16:02.543
<i> COUNCILMAN KNIGHT:</i>
<i> Hey, Arman.</i>

16:02.579 --> 16:04.379
Hey, listen, I've, uh...

16:04.414 --> 16:06.748
I have a bit of an emergency.
I need your help.

16:06.783 --> 16:09.217
Well, my hands are full, Eric.
Can it wait?

16:09.252 --> 16:10.785
<i> COUNCILMAN KNIGHT:</i>
<i> No. No, it can't wait.</i>

16:10.820 --> 16:12.654
This is a situation
that affects all of us.

16:12.689 --> 16:14.689
What is it?

16:14.724 --> 16:16.891
There's a...there's another--

16:16.926 --> 16:18.092
another councilman.

16:18.128 --> 16:20.428
His name is Charles Burton,
okay?

16:20.463 --> 16:21.763
<i> This guy's a real jackass.</i>

16:21.798 --> 16:23.898
<i> It turns out,</i>
<i> he found out about our...</i>

16:23.933 --> 16:27.101
<i> (exhales) our arrangements,</i>
<i> you know,</i>

16:27.137 --> 16:29.737
<i> and, uh, he's--he's</i>
<i> threatening to talk, he's--</i>

16:29.773 --> 16:31.572
<i> Arman, he's gonna name names.</i>

16:31.608 --> 16:33.274
How much does he want?

16:33.309 --> 16:35.143
Half a million dollars.

16:39.949 --> 16:41.716
Here's what
you're gonna do, Eric.

16:41.751 --> 16:44.052
<i> You're gonna tell him</i>
<i> he's gonna get what he wants.</i>

16:44.087 --> 16:46.921
He's just gonna have to come
by the club to get it.

16:46.956 --> 16:50.658
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

16:50.694 --> 16:55.963
<i> THONY AND SINGER: ♪ Nothing's</i>
<i> gonna hurt you, baby ♪</i>

16:55.999 --> 16:59.100
<i> (Cigarette's After Sex's</i>
<i> Nothing's Gonna Hurt You Baby)</i>

16:59.135 --> 17:01.335
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

17:01.371 --> 17:03.104
<i> ♪ As long as you're with me ♪</i>

17:03.139 --> 17:05.940
<i> ♪ You'll be just fine ♪</i>

17:05.975 --> 17:10.178
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

17:10.213 --> 17:13.881
<i> (tense music)</i>

17:13.917 --> 17:20.121
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

17:20.156 --> 17:22.156
Where is everybody?

17:22.192 --> 17:24.525
We're cleaning up
after a private event.

17:25.562 --> 17:27.195
Look, Arman,
I just want you to know

17:27.230 --> 17:30.131
this is
a one-time deal, okay?

17:30.166 --> 17:32.100
I've worked for the city
my whole life.

17:32.135 --> 17:34.469
This is my cash-out.

17:34.504 --> 17:37.004
ARMAN: Yeah, you took a big
swing, Charles, I get it.

17:37.040 --> 17:38.539
I respect that.

17:38.575 --> 17:41.008
This is
the famous La Habana, huh?

17:41.044 --> 17:42.643
Yeah.

17:42.679 --> 17:44.645
Heard a lotta great things
about this place,

17:44.681 --> 17:46.647
but never been inside.

17:46.683 --> 17:48.549
Well, we have
a very exclusive clientele,

17:48.585 --> 17:50.585
and we limit
the number of guests, so...

17:50.620 --> 17:51.986
That's true.

17:52.021 --> 17:53.921
I mean, I-I can't even get
a table here on the weekend.

17:53.957 --> 17:55.490
(light laugh)

17:55.525 --> 17:57.658
Hey, why don't I give you
a quick fifty-cent tour?

17:57.694 --> 18:00.027
-Come on.
-Yeah.

18:02.699 --> 18:06.033
<i> THONY AND SINGER:</i>
<i> ♪ With our sunglasses on ♪</i>

18:06.069 --> 18:11.272
<i> ♪ To our favorite songs... ♪</i>

18:11.307 --> 18:12.907
<i> -BURTON: No--stop!</i>
<i> -(distant gunshot)</i>

18:12.942 --> 18:15.610
<i> -(tinny music continues)</i>
<i> -(glass shatters)</i>

18:15.645 --> 18:20.481
<i> SINGER:</i>
<i> ♪ Microphone and singing... ♪</i>

18:20.517 --> 18:24.185
<i> (Burton shouting indistinctly)</i>

18:24.220 --> 18:25.853
Who else knows
about the payouts?

18:25.889 --> 18:27.388
Aah!
(gasping, whimpering)

18:27.423 --> 18:29.157
ARMAN: Who did you tell
on the council?

18:29.192 --> 18:31.392
I swear, I swear I didn't--
I didn't tell anyone.

18:31.427 --> 18:32.593
(muffled shouting)

18:32.629 --> 18:33.828
O-okay! Okay, Arman!

18:33.863 --> 18:35.563
I think he gets the message.

18:37.133 --> 18:38.099
Get out.

18:38.134 --> 18:41.569
(struggling sounds continue)

18:41.604 --> 18:42.770
ARMAN:
Get outta here!

18:42.806 --> 18:46.174
This is bad, Arman.
This is really bad.

18:46.209 --> 18:49.110
<i> (dramatic music)</i>

18:49.145 --> 18:51.779
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

18:51.815 --> 18:53.114
He's not breathing!

18:57.320 --> 18:58.553
(gags, vomits water)

18:58.588 --> 19:01.656
(gasping, coughing)

19:01.691 --> 19:02.957
ARMAN: Come on.

19:02.992 --> 19:04.959
No, no, I swear.
I swear I won't talk.

19:04.994 --> 19:06.928
-I swear I won't tell.
-You breathe a word

19:06.963 --> 19:08.596
about this to anybody,
I'll kill you.

19:08.631 --> 19:10.097
-BURTON: Uhh--
-Come on, get him

19:10.133 --> 19:12.066
the hell outta here--
come on.

19:14.771 --> 19:16.604
You could have killed him.

19:20.643 --> 19:21.809
Clean it up.

19:23.446 --> 19:25.446
This isn't
what I signed up for.

19:25.481 --> 19:29.150
You said you wanted
to pay your debts off to me.

19:29.185 --> 19:32.086
Clean it up.

19:32.121 --> 19:35.489
<i> (dark, heavy music)</i>

19:40.997 --> 19:43.331
(grunts)

19:43.366 --> 19:48.035
FIONA: Hey, what's that?
What are you doing?

19:48.071 --> 19:49.604
You okay, Thony?

19:49.639 --> 19:53.107
(sniffing)
What's that smell?

19:53.142 --> 19:56.210
There was a grease spill
at a fast food joint.

19:56.246 --> 19:58.346
Alonzo sent me.

19:59.916 --> 20:02.283
Alonzo doesn't have
any fast food places.

20:05.088 --> 20:08.256
It was in a casino.

20:08.291 --> 20:11.759
Can you just grab me
some, um, dish soap?

20:11.794 --> 20:13.394
Yeah, sure.

20:27.577 --> 20:29.176
GARRETT: Look, I'm his Dad too.

20:29.212 --> 20:31.612
I mean, can I just
bring over his bike?

20:34.317 --> 20:36.851
What? You got--
you got him the bike?

20:36.886 --> 20:39.287
Okay.
No, I mean, I thought, I--

20:39.322 --> 20:41.722
I know I told you
that I was gonna get him--

20:41.758 --> 20:43.958
okay, no, it's fine.
I gotta go.

20:43.993 --> 20:45.726
(sighs)

20:45.762 --> 20:47.128
Oh, sit.

20:49.332 --> 20:53.301
Sit down.
It's my wife.

20:53.336 --> 20:56.570
Actually, we're separated.

20:56.606 --> 20:58.806
She's having
a birthday party for him,

20:58.841 --> 21:02.243
and not only am I not invited,
but she already bought him

21:02.278 --> 21:05.746
the present that I told her
I was getting.

21:07.450 --> 21:09.483
Sorry about that.

21:10.954 --> 21:13.120
I'm glad you wanted to meet.
What's up?

21:13.156 --> 21:15.523
You said you could
offer me protection.

21:15.558 --> 21:17.258
I wanna know how.

21:18.561 --> 21:20.428
Did something happen?

21:20.463 --> 21:23.731
<i> (indistinct P.A. announcement)</i>

21:25.134 --> 21:26.300
Okay.

21:26.336 --> 21:28.169
Well, it all depends on
whether you can give us

21:28.204 --> 21:32.340
something that we can actually
use for our investigation.

21:32.375 --> 21:36.978
I won't do anything
that will endanger my life,

21:37.013 --> 21:39.680
and you have to agree
not to deport me.

21:44.988 --> 21:46.988
Thony, if you prove to me
I can trust you

21:47.023 --> 21:50.825
and give me something I can
use...you've got a deal.

21:52.795 --> 21:55.963
What kind of information
are you looking for?

21:58.067 --> 22:00.534
I hear there's
a big, fat Armenian wedding

22:00.570 --> 22:02.470
coming up
for the Barsamian family.

22:02.505 --> 22:06.173
Have you noticed Arman
up to anything unusual?

22:10.446 --> 22:12.713
It sounded like
he's in charge

22:12.749 --> 22:15.149
of collecting money as gifts.

22:18.388 --> 22:20.588
Think you can get inside?

22:20.623 --> 22:23.224
I want to know
who's giving those gifts.

22:24.660 --> 22:26.494
I'm not working the wedding.

22:26.529 --> 22:28.062
Oh.

22:28.097 --> 22:32.700
You're resourceful.
I'm sure you can figure it out.

22:32.735 --> 22:37.705
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

22:37.740 --> 22:39.640
Ah.

22:52.955 --> 22:56.424
(Nadia yelling in Spanish,
muffled)

22:59.896 --> 23:01.529
No!
The smoked salmon canapés

23:01.564 --> 23:03.597
should be served during
the cocktail hour,

23:03.633 --> 23:05.566
not during dinner.

23:05.601 --> 23:07.802
(speaking Spanish)

23:07.837 --> 23:09.070
(knocking

23:09.105 --> 23:10.938
I just finished up
in the kitchen.

23:10.973 --> 23:13.441
I could help you straighten up
in here if you'd like.

23:14.577 --> 23:16.377
You're Thony, right?

23:16.412 --> 23:18.212
Yes.

23:18.247 --> 23:20.247
You're the woman
who cleaned my party.

23:20.283 --> 23:22.550
You look...different.

23:24.654 --> 23:27.755
Yeah, I forgot
my high heels at home.

23:29.892 --> 23:31.425
I could actually use your help.

23:31.461 --> 23:33.294
This place is a disaster.

23:42.338 --> 23:44.038
How's the wedding
planning going?

23:44.073 --> 23:45.940
NADIA:
Oh, everyone is incompetent.

23:45.975 --> 23:48.142
But I think that's why
my husband's boss asked me

23:48.177 --> 23:50.311
to take care of it.

23:50.346 --> 23:52.079
Well, if you need
an extra hand

23:52.115 --> 23:53.981
setting up the wedding,
I'm happy to help.

24:00.323 --> 24:02.823
I could really use
the extra work.

24:04.327 --> 24:06.393
But I understand if you
have to ask your husband.

24:08.064 --> 24:10.698
I don't have
to ask Arman anything.

24:10.733 --> 24:13.901
When it comes to my husband,
I usually get my way.

24:17.273 --> 24:19.807
(chuckles)

24:19.842 --> 24:22.343
Thank you.

24:33.222 --> 24:36.991
Thony.
What are you doing here?

24:38.327 --> 24:39.960
I asked her to come.

24:39.996 --> 24:42.029
She needed the work,
and I needed the extra help.

24:42.064 --> 24:44.498
(speaking Spanish)

24:44.534 --> 24:46.066
Oh.

24:46.102 --> 24:47.968
(speaking Spanish)

24:49.772 --> 24:50.871
Ma'am, I'm just gonna
put this in the kitchen.

24:55.845 --> 24:58.512
Why do you care so much anyway?

24:58.548 --> 25:02.616
She's just the help,
isn't she?

25:05.955 --> 25:10.191
Just do what you want.
You always do.

25:13.996 --> 25:16.964
(upbeat Armenian folk music)

25:16.999 --> 25:23.837
♪ ♪

25:38.321 --> 25:40.387
GUEST: Ooh!

25:41.657 --> 25:45.926
(guests murmur, exclaim)

25:51.467 --> 25:54.468
(music continues)

25:54.503 --> 26:01.208
♪ ♪

26:06.415 --> 26:09.783
Today we celebrate

26:09.819 --> 26:14.822
not only the union of
my precious Isabel and Ben.

26:14.857 --> 26:17.524
But we also celebrate

26:17.560 --> 26:20.728
our history, our culture,

26:20.763 --> 26:23.197
as we join
two Armenian families.

26:24.500 --> 26:29.203
Our people have suffered
so much heartbreak and loss,

26:29.238 --> 26:32.473
our homeland torn apart by war.

26:32.508 --> 26:35.175
But no matter where we are,

26:35.211 --> 26:38.612
no matter where we go
in the world,

26:38.648 --> 26:41.815
Armenia will remain our home.

26:43.052 --> 26:46.720
Which is why
I'm proud to announce

26:46.756 --> 26:51.525
that I will be sending
my son Tarik

26:51.560 --> 26:54.662
to join the Armenian military

26:54.697 --> 26:58.666
to help reclaim our land
from Azerbaijan.

26:58.701 --> 27:01.835
I'm sure he will make us
all proud.

27:01.871 --> 27:03.837
Son.

27:03.873 --> 27:07.074
(group toast)

27:07.109 --> 27:10.878
(applause)

27:13.416 --> 27:16.383
<i> (upbeat music)</i>

27:16.419 --> 27:22.389
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

27:23.793 --> 27:25.225
Always a pleasure
to see you.

27:25.261 --> 27:26.593
Thank you for coming.
Thank you.

27:26.629 --> 27:29.697
Thank you.

27:29.732 --> 27:32.466
Thank you.
(continues indistinctly)

27:35.104 --> 27:37.237
Thank you.
(murmurs)

27:37.273 --> 27:44.111
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

27:46.248 --> 27:49.416
<i> (upbeat music continues)</i>

27:49.452 --> 27:55.756
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

28:18.114 --> 28:20.681
-(paper shuffling rapidly)
-(Arman groans)

28:20.716 --> 28:22.583
Well, I think we did it,
my friend.

28:33.395 --> 28:34.928
(clank)

28:38.134 --> 28:41.969
<i> (soft dramatic music)</i>

28:42.004 --> 28:47.341
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

28:47.376 --> 28:49.409
I used to beg my dad
to work here

28:49.445 --> 28:52.346
just so I could see you
reading under that tree.

28:53.949 --> 28:55.849
BOTH: (chuckle)

28:57.353 --> 28:58.952
Hey.

29:01.891 --> 29:03.290
What is it?

29:04.627 --> 29:08.729
Oh, nothing, I...
just needed a little air.

29:10.733 --> 29:11.999
Kay.

29:14.537 --> 29:17.571
A gift for the bride.

29:18.607 --> 29:21.041
Oh, Arman.

29:21.076 --> 29:22.676
You know I used
to love to ride.

29:22.711 --> 29:24.978
Yeah.

29:25.014 --> 29:26.880
I haven't ridden
in years now.

29:26.916 --> 29:29.516
Well, something to remind you
of the past then.

29:35.357 --> 29:37.991
Do you ever think
about the past?

29:38.027 --> 29:40.394
About us?

29:43.732 --> 29:45.833
I'm happy for you, Isabel.

29:48.537 --> 29:52.472
It wasn't me, you know.
It was my dad.

29:52.508 --> 29:54.875
That letter I wrote you?

29:54.910 --> 29:57.644
Isabel,
that was a long time ago.

29:57.680 --> 30:01.048
Yes, but my dad
made me write it.

30:01.083 --> 30:03.483
I didn't want to
break up with you.

30:03.519 --> 30:05.385
He made me do it.

30:05.421 --> 30:07.020
Why?

30:07.056 --> 30:08.488
You know my dad.

30:08.524 --> 30:11.191
I mean, you have
to marry an Armenian

30:11.227 --> 30:13.227
and think about
your children's future.

30:13.262 --> 30:15.896
-You can't date the help.
-Yeah.

30:15.931 --> 30:18.966
Oh God, I'm so sorry.

30:21.303 --> 30:23.570
It's okay.

30:28.110 --> 30:31.245
<i> (upbeat music continues)</i>

30:31.280 --> 30:38.118
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

30:41.123 --> 30:42.956
It wasn't meant to be.

31:11.553 --> 31:13.487
I'll never forget.

31:17.393 --> 31:19.526
Neither will I.

31:22.698 --> 31:24.631
(door opens)

31:27.069 --> 31:28.802
What are you doing here?

31:30.005 --> 31:32.306
Uh, I'm here to clean, sir.

31:32.341 --> 31:36.376
Yeah, in the money room?

31:36.412 --> 31:38.779
I don't think so.

31:38.814 --> 31:42.649
Are you stealing from us?
Empty your pockets.

31:47.365 --> 31:49.898
That's it, isn't it?
You're a thief.

31:49.934 --> 31:52.701
-I-I'm just working here.
-Yeah.

31:55.172 --> 31:58.140
Oh, I know you.

31:58.175 --> 32:00.976
You're the cleaning lady
who works with Arman.

32:01.012 --> 32:02.511
Oh, okay.

32:02.546 --> 32:04.480
(sniffs, clears throat)

32:04.515 --> 32:06.148
So what's going on
with you two?

32:06.183 --> 32:09.518
Is he slummin' it?
Yeah?

32:12.657 --> 32:14.423
You know, it's okay.

32:15.660 --> 32:18.727
Arman, he's an impostor too.

32:20.231 --> 32:22.865
You know, he poisoned
my own father against me.

32:22.900 --> 32:24.266
THONY: I'm sorry.

32:24.301 --> 32:26.068
Hey, let's see what
you're taking from us, huh?

32:26.103 --> 32:27.569
Empty your pockets.
Empty your pockets.

32:27.605 --> 32:29.071
Get off.
Get off me!

32:29.106 --> 32:30.439
Hey, hey!

32:30.474 --> 32:33.642
What is the matter with you?
Get outta here!

32:33.678 --> 32:35.077
She's stealing from us.

32:35.112 --> 32:36.779
That's why she won't
empty her pockets.

32:39.250 --> 32:40.716
Show him.

32:40.751 --> 32:43.719
<i> (dramatic music)</i>

32:43.754 --> 32:50.259
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

32:59.904 --> 33:01.403
(door slams shut)

33:02.840 --> 33:04.039
Don't.

33:07.511 --> 33:09.111
I'm not gonna hurt you.

33:11.282 --> 33:12.981
Don't.

33:15.219 --> 33:17.152
Are you scared of me now?

33:18.289 --> 33:20.989
You're not the man
I thought you were.

33:26.897 --> 33:29.431
What am I then?

33:29.467 --> 33:30.966
(shouts) What am I?

33:33.838 --> 33:37.473
Say it.
You think I'm a monster?

33:46.650 --> 33:48.517
You're so sanctimonious,

33:48.552 --> 33:52.187
yet you leech off me
every time you need my help.

33:52.223 --> 33:54.456
You don't get to judge me

33:54.492 --> 33:56.625
and still take
from the fruits of my labor.

33:56.660 --> 33:58.627
I only did this
to help my family.

33:58.662 --> 34:00.863
Am I so different?

34:00.898 --> 34:03.098
You didn't have
to stay with Hayak.

34:03.134 --> 34:04.666
You chose to work with him

34:04.702 --> 34:06.101
against your own
father's wishes--

34:06.137 --> 34:07.603
That's enough.

34:07.638 --> 34:10.205
You gave up your
real family for these people.

34:10.241 --> 34:13.275
These horrible people.
Was it all worth it?

34:13.310 --> 34:14.309
(thump)

34:16.580 --> 34:19.414
Next time you need help,
don't come running to me.

34:19.450 --> 34:26.321
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

34:44.909 --> 34:49.878
Arman.
How did we do with the gifts?

34:49.914 --> 34:51.847
I think you'll be pleased.

34:51.882 --> 34:54.383
You always
come through for me.

34:54.418 --> 34:55.984
One more thing.

34:56.020 --> 34:57.886
Councilman Knight texted.

34:57.922 --> 35:00.522
He cannot make it
to the wedding.

35:00.558 --> 35:02.257
Oh, that's a shame.

35:02.293 --> 35:06.061
It's not just a shame.
It's disrespectful.

35:06.096 --> 35:08.564
Why don't you go
and fetch him for me?

35:09.900 --> 35:11.500
We're just about
to head over to church.

35:11.535 --> 35:12.534
I could have somebody else
go get him--

35:12.570 --> 35:15.571
No, Arman, no.
It has to be you.

35:19.610 --> 35:21.276
I-I can't miss
the ceremony.

35:21.312 --> 35:23.045
If you leave now,

35:23.080 --> 35:24.780
maybe you can make it
back in time.

35:24.815 --> 35:28.250
Yes.
Thank you, son.

35:31.789 --> 35:33.388
See you later.

35:40.965 --> 35:43.999
<i> (tense music)</i>

35:44.034 --> 35:50.072
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

35:51.575 --> 35:52.808
(tapping)

35:52.843 --> 35:54.710
FIONA: Um, you hungry?

35:54.745 --> 35:56.311
I'm about to make
some afritada.

35:58.816 --> 36:03.151
Vote, study abroad,
get a driver's license,

36:03.187 --> 36:06.989
see the Eiffel Tower,
be a firefighter,

36:07.024 --> 36:09.725
meet my grandparents,
run for president--

36:09.760 --> 36:12.895
Chris, what are you
talking about?

36:14.031 --> 36:15.797
These are all the things
I can't do anymore

36:15.833 --> 36:17.266
because I'm undocumented.

36:17.301 --> 36:19.601
Now I'm a TNT just like you.

36:21.705 --> 36:23.205
Chris, I swear,

36:23.240 --> 36:25.040
I'll--I'll come up
with the money for the lawyer--

36:25.075 --> 36:26.208
(laughs) How?

36:26.243 --> 36:27.609
You'll never get
your life together.

36:27.645 --> 36:30.045
You're--you're a mess.

36:30.080 --> 36:31.580
I will.
I promise.

36:31.615 --> 36:33.882
Your promises
don't mean anything.

36:33.918 --> 36:35.884
All you ever do is lie.

36:42.893 --> 36:44.526
Okay.

36:47.264 --> 36:48.864
Okay, no more lies.

36:51.769 --> 36:55.537
Your--your father's not dead.

36:55.572 --> 36:57.039
What?

36:57.074 --> 37:00.876
Your real father
was a one-night stand

37:00.911 --> 37:05.547
I had in Manila, and...

37:07.117 --> 37:09.751
I knew there was
no future with him,

37:09.787 --> 37:12.387
and my last boyfriend, Jacob,

37:12.423 --> 37:14.356
had already moved
to the States,

37:14.391 --> 37:19.094
so I--I convinced him
you were his,

37:19.129 --> 37:21.997
but when we got here,
he found out the truth.

37:22.032 --> 37:23.899
Oh, my God.

37:23.934 --> 37:25.233
And I know.
I know.

37:25.269 --> 37:26.969
It was a terrible thing
to do,

37:27.004 --> 37:29.838
but I--you know,

37:29.873 --> 37:32.841
I was just young and stupid,
and I just--

37:32.876 --> 37:34.743
(crying)

37:34.778 --> 37:39.014
But I just wanted
what was best for you.

37:41.218 --> 37:44.453
Please, please
don't hate me,<i> anak.</i>

37:44.488 --> 37:48.790
I'm--I'm so sorry.

37:51.195 --> 37:52.961
(sobs)

37:52.997 --> 37:55.964
<i> (tender music)</i>

37:56.000 --> 38:02.838
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

38:26.063 --> 38:27.029
Hey.

38:29.099 --> 38:31.366
So what do you have for me?

38:44.214 --> 38:45.347
Walkie-talkies?

38:45.382 --> 38:46.548
I'm sorry.

38:46.583 --> 38:48.917
I couldn't get
what you asked for,

38:48.952 --> 38:51.086
but I didn't want
to come empty-handed.

38:54.892 --> 38:56.625
Okay.

38:56.660 --> 39:00.062
I thought you could give these
to your son for his birthday.

39:02.099 --> 39:05.734
Luca's around his age,
and he loves them.

39:12.209 --> 39:16.178
You know, when Luca
was diagnosed...

39:17.915 --> 39:19.748
Doctors gave him
a year to live.

39:22.386 --> 39:25.220
But then a birthday
went by...

39:27.491 --> 39:30.258
And another one,

39:30.294 --> 39:35.197
and another one,
and each one was a gift.

39:37.434 --> 39:39.134
I don't know what's going on
with your wife,

39:39.169 --> 39:41.770
but if you want to see
your son on his birthday,

39:41.805 --> 39:44.106
you don't have
to ask for permission.

39:44.141 --> 39:47.375
<i> ♪ ♪</i>

39:55.919 --> 39:57.886
(doorbell rings)

40:04.161 --> 40:05.627
Hey.

40:05.662 --> 40:07.729
Hey.

40:07.764 --> 40:09.531
What are you doing here?

40:09.566 --> 40:11.733
I just came to drop this off.

40:11.768 --> 40:14.136
It's walkie-talkies.

40:14.171 --> 40:16.771
Apparently, it's all the rage
with five-year-olds.

40:20.811 --> 40:23.145
Look...

40:23.180 --> 40:27.349
I know you said
you wanted boundaries, okay?

40:27.384 --> 40:30.452
And you have every right.
Every right, Colleen.

40:33.690 --> 40:38.160
But this--this isn't
about us right now.

40:38.195 --> 40:39.294
This is about Sam.

40:39.329 --> 40:42.964
It's about our boy
and his birthday.

40:44.968 --> 40:47.536
So just think about it.
All right, think about it.

40:47.571 --> 40:49.704
What--what does Sammy
get every year

40:49.740 --> 40:52.807
when we cut his birthday cake?
Huh?

40:52.843 --> 40:56.278
A visit from
the Cookie Monster--

40:56.313 --> 40:57.612
Don't.
Don't, please.

40:57.648 --> 40:59.414
(as Cookie Monster)
Colleen, please let me

40:59.449 --> 41:01.650
come to birthday party.

41:01.685 --> 41:06.188
Cookie Monster wants to eat
cookies at the birthday party.

41:07.224 --> 41:09.257
(chuckles)
Come on.

41:09.293 --> 41:12.360
Ah, there it is.
I got you.

41:12.396 --> 41:16.331
But don't deprive Sammy
of the things that he loves

41:16.366 --> 41:18.099
because of my mistakes.

41:19.803 --> 41:21.770
He's still my son.

41:34.184 --> 41:36.218
I got Luca's results.

41:36.253 --> 41:39.354
I'm afraid his liver damage is
more extensive than we thought.

41:41.258 --> 41:43.858
It's because of
the adenovirus, isn't it?

41:43.894 --> 41:45.827
Yes.

41:45.862 --> 41:47.696
He's gonna need
a liver transplant.

41:49.299 --> 41:50.498
I'm sorry, Thony,

41:50.534 --> 41:54.169
this disqualifies him
from the trial.

41:54.204 --> 41:56.438
No. No, no. No, no.

41:56.473 --> 41:58.673
We need to fix
his immune system now,

41:58.709 --> 42:00.642
or he'll never survive
a liver transplant.

42:00.677 --> 42:02.077
You know it.

42:02.112 --> 42:04.012
He needs this trial,
or he'll die.

42:04.047 --> 42:06.414
-I understand that, but--
-There has to be another way.

42:06.450 --> 42:08.717
You can use his old INR
and T-bili numbers.

42:08.752 --> 42:10.318
You can just push it through.

42:10.354 --> 42:12.654
You know
I can't do that, Thony.

42:12.689 --> 42:15.257
The rules for this trial
are strict for a reason.

42:15.292 --> 42:18.393
If just one child presents
with organ failure,

42:18.428 --> 42:20.996
it could shut the trial down
for everyone.

42:22.733 --> 42:24.399
I could pay you.

42:24.434 --> 42:27.502
(whispers) You can do the
treatment off the books.

42:28.705 --> 42:30.272
No one would have to know.

42:32.509 --> 42:34.609
Thony,
that would be unethical.

42:38.682 --> 42:40.482
I think you should leave now.

42:40.517 --> 42:43.485
<i> (dramatic music)</i>

42:43.520 --> 42:50.392
<i> ♪ ♪</i>
